“An offset is a sequential number that Kafka assigns to each message within a partition. It represents the position of the message in that partition.

Kafka tracks offsets at the consumer group level, which means each consumer group maintains its own offset for a topic partition.

When a consumer processes a message, the offset is committed—either automatically (auto-commit) or manually using acknowledgment. Kafka itself does not know whether processing was successful; the consumer is responsible for committing the offset.

If a new consumer group starts and no offset exists, the auto.offset.reset configuration determines the behavior. ‘Earliest’ means consuming messages from the beginning, while ‘latest’ means consuming only new incoming messages.”


