🔥 1️⃣ Scenario: Duplicate Message Processing
❓ Question

“What if the same Kafka message is consumed twice?”

💡 Why this happens
Consumer crashes after processing but before committing offset
Kafka will resend the message → duplicate processing
✅ Answer (Interview Ready)

“Kafka provides at-least-once delivery by default, so duplicate processing is possible. This usually happens if a consumer processes a message but fails before committing the offset.

To handle this, we make the consumer logic idempotent—for example, by checking if the data is already processed in the database or by using a unique identifier in the message.”

🔥 2️⃣ Scenario: Message Loss
❓ Question

“Can Kafka lose messages?”

💡 Explanation
If auto-commit = true
Offset committed before processing → crash → message lost
✅ Answer

“Kafka is highly durable, but message loss can happen if offsets are committed before processing is completed.

To avoid this, we disable auto-commit and use manual acknowledgment, ensuring offsets are committed only after successful processing.”

🔥 3️⃣ Scenario: Consumer Crash
❓ Question

“What happens if a consumer crashes?”

💡 Explanation
Kafka uses consumer groups + rebalancing
✅ Answer

“If a consumer crashes, Kafka triggers a rebalance within the consumer group. The partitions assigned to the failed consumer are reassigned to other active consumers.

The new consumer resumes processing from the last committed offset, ensuring no data loss, but it may reprocess some messages depending on when the last offset was committed.”

🔥 4️⃣ Scenario: More Consumers than Partitions
❓ Question

“What happens if you have 5 consumers but only 3 partitions?”

✅ Answer

“Kafka assigns one partition to only one consumer within a group. So if there are more consumers than partitions, some consumers will remain idle.

In this case, only 3 consumers will be active, and 2 will not receive any messages.”

🔥 5️⃣ Scenario: Ordering Guarantee
❓ Question

“Does Kafka guarantee message ordering?”

✅ Answer

“Kafka guarantees ordering only within a single partition. If messages are sent to the same partition—usually by using the same key—their order is preserved.

However, across multiple partitions, ordering is not guaranteed.”

🔥 6️⃣ Scenario: Retry / Failure Handling
❓ Question

“What will you do if message processing fails?”

✅ Answer

“If processing fails, we should not acknowledge the message, so Kafka can retry it.

For better handling, we can implement retry mechanisms or send failed messages to a Dead Letter Topic (DLT) for later analysis.”

🔥 7️⃣ Scenario: Lag (Important)
❓ Question

“What is consumer lag?”

💡 Explanation
Messages produced > messages consumed
✅ Answer

“Consumer lag is the difference between the latest offset in the partition and the offset last consumed by the consumer.

It indicates how far behind the consumer is. High lag means the consumer is not processing messages fast enough.”



