## 4️⃣ Interview-ready Answer (English)

> “When a producer sends messages without a key, Kafka assigns them to partitions in a round-robin manner to evenly distribute load. Each message gets a unique offset within its partition.
>
> Consumers in a consumer group are assigned one or more partitions. They read messages in order based on offsets, and commit the offset after processing. This ensures that every message is read and processed at least once, even if the producer did not provide a key.
>
> If a key is provided, Kafka hashes the key to a specific partition, which guarantees that all messages with the same key go to the same partition, preserving ordering.”

